Q1. Security Awareness Presentation
Title: "Stay Safe: Common Cyber Threats & You"

Duration: 5–7 minutes

Slide 1: Why This Matters

Cyber attacks target people, not just computers.

One wrong click can affect the entire company.

Slide 2: Threat #1 – Phishing

What it is: Fake emails pretending to be legitimate (bank, IT support, boss).

Red Flags:

Urgent language ("Act now!")

Suspicious sender email

Spelling errors

Hover over links — do they match?

Action: When in doubt, don't click. Report to IT.

Slide 3: Threat #2 – Weak Passwords

What it is: Hackers guess or steal easy passwords.

Bad examples: password123, yourname2024, same password everywhere.

Good practice:

Use long passphrases (e.g., Blue-Tiger-Coffee-9!)

Use a password manager

Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

Slide 4: Threat #3 – Unauthorized Access

What it is: Someone watching your screen, using unattended devices, or tailgating into secure areas.

Action:

Lock your screen (Windows + L)

Never share passwords or badges

Report unknown people in restricted areas

Slide 5: Threat #4 – Public Wi-Fi & Devices

What it is: Hackers intercept data on open networks.

Action:

Use VPN for company work

Avoid accessing sensitive data on public Wi-Fi

Do not leave laptops unattended in public

Slide 6: Your Role

You are the first line of defense.

If you see something suspicious → report it.

No punishment for reporting — better safe than sorry.

Slide 7: Summary

Threat	Simple Action
Phishing	Think before you click
Weak passwords	Use MFA + password manager
Unauthorized access	Lock screen, secure badge
Public Wi-Fi	Use VPN
"Security is everyone's responsibility."
